I'm a Canadian dev in Vancouver with an interest in automated agriculture as a municipal utility. I hope to prove the viability of automated resource production as a strong alternative to charity and a vicious labour market.

Bash and Python are my primary scripting tools. I enjoy C, though in my current circumstances I can't justify getting more experience. I decided to prioritize learning javascript and HTML, since webdev is eating the lunch of young conventional programmers who work at a slow pace (like I do).

After much experimentation, and soul searching, I've settled on Nodejs as my server foundation. It runs on a machine with 128MB RAM, which I use as my main host, so my yearly hosting cost is $15 [ http://tinyvz.com/ ].

My bucket list consists of making remixes to old game music, and releasing them in tracker formats, such as .xm. Open Source music promotes remix culture!

The Soundtrack highest on my priority list is Perfect Dark. Presently I am using Ableton, as I hope to hone my skills in such a way that I can moonlight as a DJ with minimal setup time. Using my remixing dream as a way to drive my most relaxing passtime seemed a good compromise until I have the financial stability to recreate them in .xm.\nhttps://xenmen.bandcamp.com/album/alone-with-joanna-dark

Writing more NDS homebrew and SDL toys would be a nice passtime. I hear Rust is nice, but I'd rather learn how to wield Nodejs and such first. My ideal future is a mobile home with rain collector, solar power, and 'soylent box', a mythical device that refines materials in the wild into delicious soylent-comparable mush.\nThat'd be living the dream :]
